plot(Boston$dis,Boston$nox, main="nox ~ dis")

attach(Boston)

for(i in 1:10){

1.1.3 (c)

set.seed(666)
degree <- 1:10
cv.error <- rep(NA,10)
for (i in degree){
    fit <- glm(nox ~ poly(dis ,i),data=Boston)
    cv.error[i] = cv.glm(Boston,fit, K=10)$delta[1]
}
cv.error
##  [1] 0.005527745 0.004054299 0.003922819 0.003893007 0.004166049
##  [6] 0.005342858 0.009582706 0.009239157 0.006884391 0.005537674
plot(degree,cv.error,type="b", ylim = c(0, 0.012))

Looks like the 3rd and 4th degree have equally lowest CV error. After 5th degree, the CV error starts to fluctuate and becomes unstable. We can repeat this step 10 times to see the variation of the CV error.

cv.error10 <- matrix(NA,nrow=10, ncol=10)
for(i in 1:10){
  set.seed(i)
  for (j in degree){    
      fit <- glm(nox ~ poly(dis ,j),data=Boston)
      cv.error10[i,j] <- cv.glm(Boston,fit, K=10)$delta[1]
  }
}
boxplot(cv.error10,ylim=c(0,0.03),xlab="degree", ylab="cv error")

# Look at the mean of cv error the each degree
colMeans(cv.error10)
##  [1] 0.005526181 0.004082282 0.003873801 0.003887038 0.004173475
##  [6] 0.005271818 0.011528008 0.006945973 0.018566623 0.013526087

Finally it turns out that the third degree (cubic spline) is the best choice according to cross-validation.

Let’s pick the node #27; the asterisk indicates the terminal node. The split criterion is ListPriceDiff > 0.135, the number of observations in that branch is 177 with a deviance of 132.90 and an overall prediction for the branch is CH. About 87.6% of the observations in that branch take the value of CH, and the remaining 12.4% take the value of MM.

plot(tree1); text(tree1, pretty = 0)

It turns out that the most important indicator of outcome variable Purchase is LoyalCH, since the top three nodes contain `LoyalCH.

As the bootstrap sample size (ntree) grows over 200, the OOB error rate becomes stable.

3.2.2 Select best hyperparameter m using CV

library(caret)
cvCtrl <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number=5, repeats=5, ## 10-fold CV repeated 10 times
classProbs=FALSE)

set.seed(666)

rf.cv <- train(x=train, y=train$y, trControl=cvCtrl,
               tuneGrid=data.frame(mtry=seq(1,30,3)),method="rf", ntree=300)

4.1.8 (h) which approach seems to give the best results

sm<-data.frame(Method=c("cost0.01","cost0.01tune","Radial kernel","Radial kernal_tune",
                        "Polynomial kernel", "Polynomial kernel_tune"),
              Training_error=c(0.154,0.146,0.135,0.139,0.171,0.138), 
              Testing_error=c(0.222,0.222,0.2,0.2,0.207,0.211))
 pander::pander(sm)
Method Training_error Testing_error
cost0.01 0.154 0.222
cost0.01tune 0.146 0.222
Radial kernel 0.135 0.2
Radial kernal_tune 0.139 0.2
Polynomial kernel 0.171 0.207
Polynomial kernel_tune 0.138 0.211

Therefore, the radial kernel approach without tuning the cost (using the default 0.01) has the best traing and testing error rate.
